Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, totaling 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought about the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria after the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of former Chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the tip.
In contrast, the election leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but it loses 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse, the ÖVP lost almost nine percent of the votes with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in post-war Austrian history, and especially of the People's Party, which demanded the early elections, this is a truly disastrous result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP had left the coalition, the People's Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
The voters, however, probably punished the party for failing the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there were speculations about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be the case on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party executive.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) received 18 per cent of the votes, the BZÖ eleven per cent - the Social Democrats expressed their fear that 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had reached agreement with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still uniform, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) regarding a common government, which had even caused sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is willing to cooperate with each party, obviously relies on this development and assumes that he will return to Vienna for Austrian federal policy.
The Green Party also moved into parliament, but suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four-percentage threshold and consequently has not moved into parliament.
