`Auto Bee' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature this time, to be more precise, by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight is due to the swarm behavior of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers from the technical development center of Nissan Motor Co. developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&D Brand Management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan security shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds up its own oval-shaped airspace, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the bee's facet eyes, which can see in all directions over an angle of 300 degrees, which allows her to fly undisturbed in her personal airspace without interruption.
To reproduce the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It detects obstacles in front of the BR23C at a distance of up to two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to a microprocessor in-vehicle, which is immediately translated into signal for avoiding collision.
`At the moment when obstacle is noticed, the small robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels around 90o or even larger angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to any other system is that this evasive maneuver is absolutely instinctive.
If it were not so, the robot could not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the chief engineer of this project.
In contrast to a bee, the robot can neither deviate upwards nor downwards, but also not diagonally; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in infinite ways that bees do.
For this reason, in addition to acceleration and braking functions, Nissan has used the rotation function so that the small robot avoids collisions.
`This device only needs a few seconds to process the information and act according to this information.
It does not require neither the information nor the intuitive logic of the manoeuvres made, therefore it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of disk space.
That sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs and not even about the MBs of the disk space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts will introduce in the next ten years in the series cars.
The robot works with lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite in order to lead to the destination while driving, avoiding obstacles on the way.
