Morgan Stanley provides her capital for MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its company, which would be the first bank in Japan to spend $9 billion and thus take over 21% of its capital, an innovation due to a strong fall in its stock market price.
One week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks declared that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a uniform price of $25.25, which would total $3 billion.
The assumed price is below 19% of the share price of August 31st.
MUFG will invest an additional six billion dollars in the acquisition of convertible shares, which will secure a 10% profit and can be resold at a price of 31.25 dollars.
Morgan Stanley explained that the global deal will be made on the basis of a single average price of $29, i.e. 28% above the current price.
However, Morgan Stanley's share fell by 6.79% to $23.07 against 17.00 GMT.
'This strategic link is an important opportunity to accelerate the transition from Morgan Stanley to the status of a holding bank,' said John Mack, Director General of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this status last week, which will allow him to expand their business into new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street's biggest names to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The arrangements presented on Monday also show that the agreement has been changed over the last few days: last Monday Morgan simply stated that she would sell up to 20% of her shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
'A week ago,' said Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG, in Tokyo, 'we thought that the holding would consist entirely of common shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and secure ourselves.'
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below its price value for its Morgan Stanley shares.
And the business will go with a reduction in profit of about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preference shares into common shares in one year if the latter are exchanged to more than 50% above the sale value within a given period, i.e. to approximately $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds provided by MUFG will allow him to use investment opportunities, strengthen their balance sheet and increase their sales.
However, a group press spokesman refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG's investment, Morgan Stanley should be able to record a solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan explained that he has 'significantly' lowered his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been tough for the group that had to watch their stock market price fall by half, while the price of insurance against insolvency has increased.
This price declined on Monday, but remained at a high level, at about 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other 'survivors' of the major investment banks on Wall Street after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that they have raised 15 billion dollars, partly at Berkshire Hathaway, the Warren Buffett group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Refounding the Republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorial Rafael Correa.
It was that third party who, following the example of his like-minded and friends, put the plan for a new constitution for election this Sunday.
Mission accomplished, because according to the public results, which amounted to 80% of the votes, 64% voted 'yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'no', 7% of the ballot papers were invalid and 0.7% were empty.
In order for the constitutional project to be adopted, more than half of all votes cast must be cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a census of a non-governmental organisation announced a clear victory for 'yes', and 63% to 70% predicted it.
By the way, Rafael Correa had demanded the victory of his constitutional project on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The 'Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly', he had assured in Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Equatorialians.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held silently according to the observational delegation of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text consisting of 444 points to secure the 'new socialism' for which the President is committed.
The constitutional project transfers the state power to the economy by giving it the sole right to 'development planning' in a country that largely lives from oil production by foreign companies and foreign exchange sending immigrants to the country.
The project, promoted by the 2006 elected Correa, also grants the head of state greater power, which will be able to exercise up to two successive mandates of four years each, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will make use of this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also guarantees the principle of free medical care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country with 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Equatorian base as a base for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the attack on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions who had been captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were detained in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital this Monday afternoon in a healthy and intact manner.
In the morning they had been liberated by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages reached the military base of al-Maza right next to the Cairo International Airport at around 3.30 p.m. on board a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being able to speak to the press, aboard a helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a foreigner's district of Cairo, to be examined there.
They all enjoy 'best health' and 'no ransom was paid' to the kidnappers, said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the runway.
After being taken prisoner on September 19 at an off-road vehicle safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken by 35 unknown hijackers from one hiding place to the next.
They are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two guides, four chauffeurs, one border guard and the director of the agency Egyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer explained that 30 members of the special forces, from board two helicopters, launched the attack at night shortly before dawn.
'On both sides, shots were fired and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled,' said this person in charge, who wants to remain anonymous.
He explained that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomat Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade, where he is now, on the role, the secret agents and elements of the Italian Special Forces.
'We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the intelligence service and the special forces,' he explained without further detail.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
On the eve of the day, the Sudanese army claimed to have stopped an off-road vehicle in a patrol, where the hijackers were, six of them, including the leader from Chad, and two arrests.
The army stated that they were associated with a rebel group from Darfur, the Libération du Soudan-Unité (SLA-U), but immediately denied this movement.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and is the central topic of the current election campaign.
That's all the better.
But an area of our cultural life remains in oblivion.
Who will stand up and denounce the pitiful sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical places that starve miserably?
Which politician will dare to remind the Federal Government that it neglects its monuments and culturally important buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, there are no proper laws that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is providing EUR 3.5 million solely for the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley?
Our American neighbours have written in their country's constitution that the protection of cultural heritage is part of the American culture, and that this cultural heritage must be protected by all citizens, by all members of parliament and by all government, in mutual agreement.
In Quebec, in the association of Quebec’s historical societies, at least 40,000 volunteers gathered in 211 historical societies are working hard on history, saving the numerous private archives with a few penny, and preserving the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage, protesting with the power of despair when promoters and decision makers release their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and cultural heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalisation, the Benelux states want to help the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which is in turmoil as a result of the US financial crisis: the three states are making a total of EUR 11.2 billion available to the bank and insurance institution, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands discussed this weekend at the highest level, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner of the Competition Authority of the European Commission.
In the euro area, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial crisis that has been ongoing for a year, so decisions that are now being taken in connection with the bank could have a precedent.
In line with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states buy approximately 49 percent of the bank’s respective shares.
The bank will probably sell part of its stakes, especially the insurance activities purchased by the Dutch ABN Amro last year.
The shares of Fortis started a steep descent last week, and serious crisis scenarios were already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too large for a bankruptcy.
The Institute's securities fell 12% to a 14-year low on Friday.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
In view of the current share prices, the market value of the Group amounts to EUR 14 billion, which is unrealistic according to management.
According to management, the USD 700 billion US rescue package and the resulting uncertainty in the markets are responsible for the decline in Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, the courses increased slightly.
On Friday Filip Dierckx was appointed new Director General of the Bank.
The institute was also looking for a private buyer, but it did not find any interested party with an objective offer.
The Belgian government, however, tried to calm down - no investor should tremble for his money, they said.
No panic has erupted among the customers, the bank's branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but also names its own leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
Due to a person's drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to sign a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of the drug data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox to the chickens" - quotes the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for tracking prescription data.
Insurance companies determine the fees and payment amounts in the event of damage, depending on the health status of the customer, and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance is not taken out at all.
In the past, the customer was sent to a medical examination and the contract was concluded only in knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: Based on the customer's identification number, he obtains the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, i.e., which preparations were bought, and the program calculates the illness the customer suffers from and how his health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it would be possible to conclude that his blood fat levels are untreatable, which would automatically put him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so the insurance companies only have to do the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the drawbacks is that many medicines can be taken for various purposes, such as migraines and hot flushes, but also depression.
The latter is a high risk factor from the point of view of insurers, while the previously mentioned is not.
For the query and processing of the data, own societies have formed which, before they obtain the data, ask the patient for his consent.
Meanwhile, they have to do this by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with the data on drug use. Thus, they provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data and control of their use is becoming more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect only extends to service providers in the health sector and insurance.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is too little, so he wants to further develop his program so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question, of course, is that the data subject can hardly prevent access to his data, as the insurance companies do not otherwise conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are more or less left to the mercy of the fox.
Global food plan from Marseille
European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this was the main issue, among other global problems, at the ninth summit.
Today, the French-Indian summit is also taking place, which mainly discusses cooperation in the nuclear sector.
While the European Union recognises that India is an emerging, democratic great power that should be given more voice and voice in international concerns, Member States have not yet been able to agree whether or not to support the permanent membership of New Delhi in the UN Security Council.
This question was not discussed at the ninth summit yesterday in Marseille.
French President and current EU President Nicolas Sarkozy, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade over the next five years, i.e. to a good 100 billion euros.
Given that trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this target is not even so ambitious.
In this sense, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have also been legally merged into one agreement, so that in future aviation will also be boosted.
By 2009, India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance in the currently unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is the number one partner in India, New Delhi is only ninth among EU partners.
The summit was devoted to global concerns.
Among them was the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, and the convening of a UN conference was also hurried.
The Doha Round should also be concluded, with both sides to blame for failure.
The EU stressed that it is sticking to its energy and climate programme, i.e. reducing pollutant emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed to this, as did the proposal to make a kind of global compromise at the coming climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
The increase in food prices should also be combated, so both support the convening of an international conference on the financial crisis.
The Indian head of government is visiting the French capital today, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, however, orders to French companies worth EUR 20 billion are expected for the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to the Agency, the agreement is to be concluded for 15 years.
More than 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the International Frankfurt Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th Book Fair, the most important international event for the acquisition of rights.
The international Frankfurt Book Fair is expecting more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries for the current event. They will spread over the 171,790 square meters of the fair and present over 403,000 titles. Turkey will be the honorary guest of the event.
The Undersecretary for the Ministry of Cultural Property and Activities Maria Giro will represent the Italian Government in the exhibition hall during the opening ceremony: Italy will be represented in the 264 sqm exhibition space "Punto Italia".
This will be followed by a press conference near the Room Structure in the Exhibition Hall 5.0 of the Book Fair: on this occasion, figures, trends and perspectives relating to publishing in Italy will be discussed.
According to the data, the importance of books by foreign writers in the whole, but in particular in the adult and youth sectors decreases.
The billionaire Steve Fossett's small aircraft disappeared a year ago
The small aircraft of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007 was found.
The items have been found on a 3000 m high plateau, in the area of the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states of California and Nevada.
However, there were no human remains inside the aircraft.
The sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, completely dispelled the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located to which a troop has been sent. Now we have the certainty that it is the plane with which Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found in the plane or near it.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Department of Traffic Safety (Ntsb) noted that a team was sent out just hours after the aircraft was sighted, identifying the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett had started a 3-hour flight in Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, some of Fossett's personal belongings were finally found in California, not far from the Nevada border, by a couple near their home on Mammoth Lakes.
These are two passports with the name Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had gained a place in history through a long succession of records.
In 2002, he succeeded in the sixth attempt, as the first person to circle the world ball in a hot air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world on a single flight without stopping by plane.
Among his many records is also an altitude flight of 15445 m over the Andes, which, however, with a co-pilot.
